SIMON WEISEND

Notes for AUGUSTINA M. HAREN:

 

Relatives and friends were shocked Sunday evening to learn of the sudden death of Miss

Gussie Haren, of Columbus. Miss Haren had been ill for the past two weeks with

influenza at the St. Francis Hospital, Columbus, but was thought to be improving nicely.

Her death Sunday noon, February 1943, was unexpected. She was 58 years of age.

 

Miss Haren was a daughter of the late John and Matilda Weisend Haren of Woodsfield, and was a resident of Woodsfield, most of her life. She was an employee of the Monroe Bank for several years. She had recently been employed at the Ia! Lal Cafe in Columbus.

 

Surviving axe four sisters and two brothers, Mrs. Frances Weisend, of Akron; Mrs. Bertha

Stider, of Cleveland; Miss Clementine Haren of Dennison; Miss Grace Haren, of

Columbus; John Haren, of Louisville, Ky., and Clarence Haren, of Los Angeles, Calif.

Two aunts, Miss Cecelia Weisend, of Woodsfield, and Mrs. Philomena Staudt, of

Columbus, also survive.

 

Funeral services will be held Wednesday morning at 9:00 o'clock at Our Lady of Victory Church in Columbus. Burial will be made at Columbus.

Notes for EDNA ANN CRUM:

WOODSFIELD - Edna A. Haren, 93, of South Sycamore Street died Saturday (Feb. 9, 2002) at Barnesville Hospital.

 

She was born Sept. 17, 1908, in Noble County to George and Gertrude Ritterbeck Crum. She was a member of St. Sylvester Catholic Church at Woodsfield and the Catholic Women's Club.

 

She is survived by several nieces and nephews.

 

She was preceded in death by her husband, Clem Haren, in 1965; six sisters, Mary Dimmerling, Matilda Kullman, Emma Haren, Blach Nauer, Cora Michel and Estella Sebold; and four brothers, Lewis, Raymond, Urban and Harry Crum.

 

Mass of Christian burial is at 11 a.m. today at St. Sylvester Catholic Church at Woodsfield with Father David Gaydosik officiating. Burial is in St. Sylvester Catholic Church Cemetery. Bauer-Turner Funeral Home in Woodsfield is in charge of arrangements.

Notes for CLEMENTINE SCHUMACHER:

MRS. FRANK HAREN

 

Mrs. Frank (Clementine) Haren, 72, of 1963 Central Avenue, Middletown, Ohio passed away early Tuesday morning on June 21, 1952 in a hospital at Middletown.. She suffered a stroke on Sunday, June 14th.

 

A daughter of the late John and Catherine Weisend Schumacher, she was born December

3, 1880, north of Woodsfield. Forty-four years ago the Haren family moved to Sidney

where they resided for a short time before going to Middletown where they have resided.

 

Surviving are one son, Raymond Haren, and one grandson, Jimmy Hai~n, of Middletown; two sisters, Miss Anna Schumacher and Miss Emma Schumacher, and one brother, Benjamin Schumacher, all of Woodsfleld. Her husband preceded her in death seventeen years ago.

 

Funeral services will be held this Thursday morning in Holy Trinity Church at Middletown, with interment in that city.

Notes for JOHN GEORGE BURKHART:

John G. Burkhart, 83, of 300 South Sycamore Street, Woodsfield, died Thursday morning, February 23, 1967, at his home following a brief illness.

He was bron January 20, 1884, at Ozark, Ohio, the son of the late Anthony and Mry Burkhardt Burkhart.

Mr. Burkhart was a retired oil field worker and for the past twelve years had been custodian of St. Sylvester's Catholic Church, Woodsfield.

He was a member of St. Sylvester's Church and a member of the Holyl Name Society and the Purgatorial Society.

Surviving are his wife, Stella Haren Burkhart; three sons, Gervase H. Burkhart, of Mission, TX, Ambrose Burkhart of Lincoln, NE. and Joseph Burkhart of Kernersville, NC; one daughter, Mrs. Mary Dorothy Froehlich of the home; eight grandchildren; one sister, Sister Mary Otto of Covington, KY and two brothers, Otto A. Burkhart of Beallsville, R2, and Laurence A. Burkhart of Wshington, DC.

A Solemn Reguiem Mass was solemnized on Monday morning at 10 o;clock in St. Sylvester's Church with the Very Reverend Monsignor Robert A. Brown as celebrant. Rev. Albert Kunkel, of Cleveland, a grand nephew of Mr. Burkhart, was deacon and Mr. Mark Froehlich was acting subdeacon.

The following dignitaries were present for the <<<<<<< HEAD funeral Mass: Very Reverend Monsignor William R. Wearsch, Rector of St. John ======= funeral Mass: Very Reverend Monsignor William R. Wearsch, Rector of St. John >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 Vianney Seminary, Bloomingdale; Rev. Ronald J. Cox, professor at St.John Vianney Seminary, and Rev. Joseph Finan, Pastor of St. Joseph's Church, Burkhart.

The Mass was sung by the Sisters and student of St. Sylvester Church.

Burial was in the church cemetery with the Michener Funeral Home in charge of arrangements.

Notes for MICHAEL SCHARIO HAREN:

Michael S. Haren, age 63, of 8735 Alberta Beach St. NE Louisville was dead on arrival at Alliance City Hospital Saturday morning Aug. 1 [1981] following a sudden illness.

Born in Canton, Ohio July 7, 1918 to the late Sylvester and Anna Schario Haren, he lived in this area all his life. He worked many years as a bricklayer retiring last year. He was a member of Bricklayers Local #6 of Canton. An Army veteran of WWII, he was stationed at Pearl Harbor during the bombing on Dec. 7, 1941. He was a member of Sacred Heart of Mary Catholic Church, Harrisburg.

He is survived by his wife, Mary Rose (Cachat) Haren of the home, 5 daughters, Mary Ann and Mary Rose Haren of Los Angeles, Cal., Mary Louise, Mary Therese, and Mary Pat Haren, all of the home; two sons, Michael P. Haren and John Haren, both of Louisville, one sister, Mrs. Mello (Alice) Maurer of Louisville; one brother, Robert Haren of Magnolia, and one granddaughter, Linnea. He was preceded in death by 4 brothers, Sylvester, Bernard, Richard, and Earl; and one sister, Mildred.

A Mass of Christian Burial was sung at Sacred Heart of Mary Church Tuesday, Aug 4 at 10 A.M. Friends called at the Paquelet Funeral Home Monday Aug. 3. Burial was in the church cemetery.

Notes for SYLVESTER B. BURKHART:

Sylvester B. Burkhart, 90, formerly of East Pike, died at 1:57 p.m. Sunday, October 23, 1994, at Willow Haven Nursing Home after a brief illness.

Born April 22, 1904, in Lewisville, Monroe County, Mr. Burkhart was a member of St. <<<<<<< HEAD Nicholas Catholic Church. He retired in ======= Nicholas Catholic Church. He retired in >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 1975 as an auto mechanic for Triangle Motor Sales Co. after 50 years of service.

Dietenbeck Burkhart, who he married June 16, 1931; three daughters and sons-in-law, Eleanor A. and Walter Flack of New Albany, Rosalia A. and Bill Parry and Mary <<<<<<< HEAD A. and James McKee, all of Zanesville; ======= A. and James McKee, all of Zanesville; >>>>>>> ef9da23e9f6816b69f175e37096e452723be7711 four sons and daughters-in-law, John R. and Mary Burkhart of Howard, Lawrence D and Laurel Burkhart, Thomas J. and Sue Burkhart and James V. and Ann Burkhart, all of Zanesville; a sister, Sister M. Adelaide Burkhart of Tiffin; 13 grandchildren, 17 great grandchildren and two great great grandchildren.

He was preceded in death by his parents, Jacob and Rosalia Haren Burkhart, a son Bernard Burkhart, a sister, and four brothers.

Notes for JOSEPHINE MARY BURKHART:

 

LOUISVILLE - Josephine M. Zwick, 96, died Thursday at St. Joseph Care Center following an extended illness.

She was born March 28, 1902 in Woodsfield, a daughter of the Nick and Mary Ann Burkhart.

Mrs. Zwick was a member of St. Louis Catholic Church and St. Ann's Altar and Rosary Society.

Surviving are a daughter, Ann Willour of Ocala, Fla.; two sisters, Mary Crum of Knoxville, Tenn. and Pauline Weisend of Woodsfield; seven grandchildren and one great-grandchild.

She was preceded in death by her husband, Clem G.; a daughter, Carolyn Kittinger; a son, Bob; three sisters; and two brothers.

A Mass of Christian burial will be celebrated at 10 a.m Monday at St. Louis Catholic Church with the Monsignor Ken Miller officiating. Burial will be in the church cemetery.

Calling hours are 2-4 p. m. Sunday at Paquelet-Falk Funeral Home.

Kathleen Haren Yoss, 76, 98 Orchard Lane, Woodsfield, died Tuesday, October 6, 1998 at Wheeling Hospital. She was born in Monroe County, June 25, 1922, a daughter of the late Richard and Louise Schwall Haren.

In addition to her parents, she was preceded in death by her first husband, Wilbur Yoss; her second husband, Arol Edington; a sister, Lucille Yoss; two brothers, Cyrel Haren and Richard J. Haren.

Surviving are two sons, Richard Yoss of Woodsfield and Gary Yoss of Caldwell; two daughters, Karen Baker of Woodsfield and Sharon Yoss of Wilson Lake; a sister, Lela Hunnell of Woodsfield; 12 grandchildren ; 11 great grandchildren.

Notes for CAROLYN JEAN ZWICK:

Carolyn Jean Kittinger, age 58, of Louisville , passed away Friday evening at Timken Mercy Medical Center following a short illness. She was born April 4, 1935 in Louisville, the daughter of Clement and Josephine (Burkhart) Zwick. She was a former assistant credit manager for the Timken Co., and spent the last 14 years with the Louisville YMCA as coordinator of the child care program. She was an active member of St. Louis Church.

Mrs. Kittinger is survived by her husband, Bruce, of Louisville; her mother, Josephine (Burkhart) Zwick of Louisville, two daughters, Elizabeth of Buffalo Grove, IL and Mary Jo of Louisville; two sons, and a daughter-in-law, Thomas of Louisville and Michael and Clarissa of Dalton; a sister, Ann Willour of Ocala, FL; and a brother, Robert Zwick of Westlake.

A Mass of Christian Burial was held Tuesday at 10:00 a.m. in St. Louis Catholic Church with Rev. Fr. Frederick Slaven officiating. Burial was in the church cemetery. Friends called Wednesday evening at the Paquelet Funeral Home of Louisville. Memorial contributions may be made to St. Louis Church.

Notes for JOHN MICHAEL ARCHER:

 

John Michael Archer, 60, Barnesville, died Monday evening at Star Nursing Home, Morristown. He was born May 28, 1928 at Woodsfield, a son of Hildred Armbruster Archer and the late Fred Archer.

 

He was a retired manager of production control for Western Union, Chicago, and a member of Assumption Catholic Church, Barnesville.

 

Surviving in addition to his mother, a resident of Barnesville, are his wife, Julia Gardner

Archer of Chicago; a son, James of Waverly, ilL; two daughters Kaye Ellen Glazer of

Waverly and Bonnie Busa of Orland Park, Ill; a brother, Bill of Woodsfield; seven

grandchildren.

 

Friends will be received at the Campbell-Plumly Funeral Home, Barnesville, 2 to 4 and 7 to 9 p.m. today. Mass of Christian Burial will be celebrated at 10 a.m. Thursday at Assumption Catholic Church, with the Rev. Charles Mascolino, the celebrant. Burial will be in Oaklawn Cemetery, Woodsfield. Rosary devotions at 8 p.m. today.
